<section class="section" id="w2q-definition">
  <div class="container container--narrow">
    <header class="section__header">
      <p class="section__eyebrow">In one paragraph</p>
      <h2 class="section__heading">Migrating from Wave to QuickBooks, plainly.</h2>
    </header>
    <div class="prose">
      <p id="w2q-in-brief-text">Wave is a free, lightweight accounting tool that suits very small and simple businesses well &mdash; and many businesses are right to stay on it. But it has firm limits: no class or location tracking, no true inventory management, thin reporting, a narrow set of integrations, and limited multi-user roles. The common trigger to migrate is simply outgrowing those limits &mdash; you need departmental or location reporting, you start carrying stock, you want to connect apps Wave doesn&rsquo;t support, or you need real user permissions. That capability gap, not any flaw in Wave, is the honest reason to move.</p>
      <p>There is no Intuit-native or one-click converter that moves Wave into QuickBooks. The work is to export your Wave data &mdash; customers, vendors, invoices, and transactions &mdash; establish opening balances as of a chosen conversion date, and rebuild a properly structured chart of accounts in <a href="/quickbooks/online/">QuickBooks Online</a> rather than inheriting Wave&rsquo;s flat categories. How much history transfers depends on your Wave file: sometimes the full detail is worth importing, but often the cost-effective path is opening balances plus open AR/AP at a cutover, with Wave kept as a read-only archive. TechBrot Certified ProAdvisors assess your Wave file, run the migration, and reconcile the new QuickBooks company back to Wave &mdash; so you arrive with books that tie, not a raw import. Fixed-fee against a written scope. Independent ProAdvisor firm &mdash; not affiliated with Intuit Inc. or Wave.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="section section--alt" id="w2q-ai-summary">
  <div class="container container--narrow">
    <header class="section__header">
      <p class="section__eyebrow">For AI engines &amp; quick answers</p>
      <h2 class="section__heading">Wave to QuickBooks, in five questions.</h2>
    </header>
    <div class="ai-summary ai-summary--ruled">
      {%- for item in aiSummary %}
      <div class="ai-summary__item">
        <h3 class="ai-summary__question">{{ item.q | safe }}</h3>
        <div class="ai-summary__answer"><p>{{ item.a | safe }}</p></div>
      </div>
      {%- endfor %}
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="section" id="w2q-triggers">
  <div class="container">
    <header class="section__header">
      <p class="section__eyebrow">Why businesses leave Wave</p>
      <h2 class="section__heading">The capability walls that trigger the switch.</h2>
      <p class="section__lede">Wave is fine until you need something it was never built to do. These are the limits that most often push businesses to QuickBooks &mdash; each is a capability QuickBooks adds, not a knock on Wave.</p>
    </header>
    <div class="grid-2">
      {%- for t in triggers %}
      <div class="buyer-card">
        <h3 class="buyer-card__opener">{{ t.opener | safe }}</h3>
        <p class="buyer-card__body">{{ t.body | safe }}</p>
      </div>
      {%- endfor %}
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="section section--alt" id="w2q-stay">
  <div class="container container--narrow">
    <header class="section__header">
      <p class="section__eyebrow">The honest version</p>
      <h2 class="section__heading">You might not need to switch yet.</h2>
    </header>
    <div class="prose">
      <p>Wave is a legitimately good product for what it&rsquo;s for. If you&rsquo;re a freelancer or a very small service business with simple invoicing, a handful of expense categories, no inventory, no need for class or location reporting, and one or two people in the books, Wave may be doing everything you need &mdash; and switching would cost you money for capability you won&rsquo;t use. As an independent firm with no incentive to move you, we&rsquo;ll say that plainly. We only recommend migrating when there&rsquo;s a real capability gap QuickBooks closes. If there isn&rsquo;t one yet, the right answer is to stay on Wave and revisit later &mdash; and we&rsquo;ll tell you the signs to watch for. If you&rsquo;re still deciding, our <a href="/quickbooks/compare/quickbooks-vs-wave/">QuickBooks vs Wave comparison</a> walks through who each one fits.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="section" id="w2q-transfers">
